'''Adam Muto''' (born July 19, 1980) is an American writer, director and storyboard artist, known for his work as the executive producer and [[showrunner]] of the animated television series ''[[Adventure Time]]''.

==Career==
Muto was a classmate of ''Adventure Time'' creator [[Pendleton Ward]] at [[CalArts]].<ref name=cbrewquit/> When Ward was first working on the ''Adventure Time'' pilot for the [[Frederator]] [[:wikt:incubation|incubator]] series ''[[Random! Cartoons]]'', Muto assisted him by drawing props.<ref name=awnrandom>{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/articles/people/random-thoughts-frederator-cartoonists/page/1%2C1|title=Random Thoughts from Frederator Cartoonists|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|first=Andrew|last=Farago|accessdate=July 14, 2010|date=January 29, 2009}}</ref> Eventually, Muto went on to work on the television series, serving as a storyboard artist. During the show's first season, he was partnered with Elizabeth Ito, but during the show's second and third seasons, he was partnered with [[Rebecca Sugar]]. During the following year, he was promoted to creative director, and midway through the show's [[Adventure Time (season 5)|fifth season]], he was promoted to supervising producer, then co-executive producer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Noelene|title='Adventure Time' Exclusive Clip|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/tv/adventure-time-exclusive-clip-adam-muto-on-the-shows-evolution/#/0|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=April 27, 2014|date=February 25, 2014}}</ref> From mid-season five until the show's conclusion, he served as the show's [[showrunner]] and executive producer (following Ward's stepping down sometime during the production of season five).<ref name=cbrewquit>{{cite web|last1=Amidi|first1=Amid|title=Pen Ward Quit ‘Adventure Time’ Because It Was Driving Him Nuts|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/tv/pen-ward-quit-adventure-time-because-it-was-driving-him-nuts-104191.html|publisher=[[Cartoon Brew]]|accessdate=June 27, 2015|date=October 3, 2014}}</ref>

==Awards==
Adam Muto's work on ''Adventure Time'' gained him a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for the [[Adventure Time (season 2)|second season]] episode "[[It Came From the Nightosphere]]" in 2011, along with his then-storyboarding partner [[Rebecca Sugar]].<ref name=emmyssitearchive>{{cite web|title=Adventure Time|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/adventure-time|work=''Emmys.com''|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>

